WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:06.910
You can get work done a number of different ways on Z.

2
00:00:06.910 --> 00:00:11.710
Some people prefer a fully graphical experience, like what you get through Zoe.

3
00:00:11.710 --> 00:00:15.710
Other people like to keep it simple, but still want a little graphical context,

4
00:00:15.710 --> 00:00:18.410
like what you get through the panels of ISPF.

5
00:00:18.410 --> 00:00:22.910
Then there's some people who really just don't want anything between them and the system,

6
00:00:22.910 --> 00:00:26.410
and they prefer to issue commands straight through TSO.

7
00:00:26.410 --> 00:00:30.410
In ZOS, TSO stands for Time Sharing Option,

8
00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:37.410
and it's basically the environment that lets the OS be made available to multiple users at the same time.

9
00:00:37.410 --> 00:00:43.410
There are a ton of commands in TSO, and this lesson, we're going to take a look at just a few of them.

10
00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:47.410
There are three primary ways of entering TSO commands.

11
00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:52.410
One, through the ISPF primary menu, going to option number 6.

12
00:00:52.410 --> 00:00:56.410
Two, on the command option line of an ISPF panel,

13
00:00:56.410 --> 00:01:01.410
on that line, anything that starts with TSO will be interpreted as a TSO command.

14
00:01:01.410 --> 00:01:05.410
And three, on the TSO ready prompt screen.

15
00:01:05.410 --> 00:01:08.410
When you do it this way, it's known as native mode.

16
00:01:08.410 --> 00:01:13.410
A command is made up of a command name, followed by one or more operands.

17
00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:16.410
Think of it like the command is the thing that you want done,

18
00:01:16.410 --> 00:01:20.410
and the operands are the details of how you'd like it to be done.

19
00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:25.410
For example, if I were to tell you move something, you would need more information,

20
00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:28.410
like what am I moving, where am I moving it to,

21
00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:33.410
am I moving it with a forklift, a train, a truck, or am I just carrying it with my hands.

22
00:01:33.410 --> 00:01:36.410
The how goes in the operands.

23
00:01:36.410 --> 00:01:42.410
Commands and operands are not case sensitive, meaning they can be typed out in lowercase or uppercase.

24
00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:48.410
We'll often type them out in uppercase though, just so they stand out more as commands and not random text.

25
00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:52.410
There are two types of operands, positional and keywords.

26
00:01:52.410 --> 00:01:57.410
A positional operand needs to come after the command and in a certain order.

27
00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:03.410
The documentation for commands will tell you exactly what order they need to be in and which ones are required.

28
00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:06.410
And we'll get into how you get that information shortly.

29
00:02:06.410 --> 00:02:08.410
There's also keyword operands.

30
00:02:08.410 --> 00:02:12.410
This is usually used to turn on a feature or set a certain mode.

31
00:02:12.410 --> 00:02:16.410
So in this example, the command is list ds.

32
00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:18.410
That's what we want it to do.

33
00:02:18.410 --> 00:02:22.410
We learned earlier that list ds stands for list dataset,

34
00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:26.410
and we can use it to show us a whole bunch of information about a dataset.

35
00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:33.410
The positional operand is something that comes right after the command name, and that's the dataset we're listing.

36
00:02:33.410 --> 00:02:39.410
One additional thing to note here, if what you want to put in the operand is a list of multiple items,

37
00:02:39.410 --> 00:02:41.410
you just put that list in parentheses.

38
00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:44.410
And then lastly is the keyword operand.

39
00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:48.410
That tells the command to list the members of this dataset.

40
00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:55.410
For this lesson, we'll be referencing the zos-tsoe command reference manual attached to this lesson.

41
00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:58.410
It's a good book. A lot better than the movie version.

42
00:02:58.410 --> 00:03:06.410
You can use the help command to obtain information about the function, syntax, and operands of the commands and subcommands,

43
00:03:06.410 --> 00:03:09.410
as well as information about certain messages.

44
00:03:09.410 --> 00:03:17.410
So you can type help list ds operands, and you'll get a listing of all the operands for the list ds command.

45
00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:24.410
You can also type help list ds all, and you'll get all the information about the list ds command.

46
00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:28.410
In the next lesson, we'll take a look at the allocate and delete commands.
